If I was going to argue against myself though, I'd argue that pre-social media, an idea had to be more vetted to gain traction because traction was a higher hurdle.  When you lower the hurdle, you lower the vetting, and make free speech a more slippery slope downward

Remember in 2005, we were all talking about how awesome blogging was going to be because the big media companies couldn't censor us anymore.  Now we are begging them to be censors.  It's not an easy problem to solve.

(5/5) It seems like it should be an easy problem to solve but, it's not. Because "hate speech" has grey areas.  You have to tolerate some messiness.  And you can't respond with one offs - you need a policy.

(4/5) isn't censored?  So again, we have two options - 1) make sure all hate speech (by whatever definition you use) gets blocked but sometimes non-hate speech is blocked out of caution too, or, 2) make sure all non-hate speech gets through but acknowledge some will creep through

(3/5) slide through.  The real tradeoff is, do we want to clamp down tougher and censor some non-hate speech to make sure we catch most of the hate speech, or, do we set a looser policy and let some hate speech unfortunately slide through, to make sure 100% of non-hate speech

(2/5) it really gets tricky where there is something that only 20% think is hate speech, but it's a very vocal 20% that seems on social media like 80%. Who defines what is "right"?  If you don't have a clear answer to that, then best to err on the side of letting some things

(1/5) People don't understand how tricky and nuanced this debate is https://t.co/jgemffD1ue  What counts as "hate speech" is a sliding scale, depending on your view.  Some things 99% of us agree are hate speech, but some, only 50% of us agree are hate speech, and...

text: @bengreene @brianmwang @robgo I actually think too many startups focus on PMF as the holy grail.  But if you read Steve Blank's original book on customer development, PMF is only step 1.  There are 3 more steps to building a successful company, all just as likely to fail.
